TY  - JOUR
T1  - Why Do Option Prices Predict Stock Returns? The Role of Price Pressure in the Stock Market
AU  - Goncalves-Pinto, Luis
AU  - Grundy, Bruce D.
AU  - Hameed, Allaudeen
AU  - van der Heijden, Thijs
AU  - Zhu, Yichao
Y1  - 2020/01/24
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2020/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3398
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3398
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3903
EP  - 3926
VL  - 66
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Stock and options markets can disagree about a stock?s value because of informed trading in options and/or price pressure in the stock. The predictability of stock returns based on this cross-market discrepancy in values is especially strong when accompanied by stock price pressure, and it does not depend on trading in options. We argue that option-implied prices provide an anchor for fundamental stock values that helps to distinguish stock price movements resulting from pressure versus news. Overall, our results are consistent with stock price pressure being the primary driver of the option price-based stock return predictability.This paper was accepted by Tyler Shumway, finance.
AB  - Stock and options markets can disagree about a stock?s value because of informed trading in options and/or price pressure in the stock. The predictability of stock returns based on this cross-market discrepancy in values is especially strong when accompanied by stock price pressure, and it does not depend on trading in options. We argue that option-implied prices provide an anchor for fundamental stock values that helps to distinguish stock price movements resulting from pressure versus news. Overall, our results are consistent with stock price pressure being the primary driver of the option price-based stock return predictability.This paper was accepted by Tyler Shumway, finance.
